**Clinical Reasoning:**
The infant presents with signs consistent with hyperthyroidism—tachycardia (pulse 176/min), tachypnea (RR 42/min), fever (38.9°C), diaphoresis, irritability, and a midline neck swelling—all of which align with neonatal transplacental transmission of maternal TSH receptor antibodies. The mother has a history of Graves’ disease, specifically undergoing thyroidectomy due to uncontrolled symptoms, indicating autoimmunity against TSH receptors. Such antibodies cross the placenta and can stimulate the fetal thyroid, leading to transient neonatal hyperthyroidism. This contrasts with transient gestational thyrotoxicosis, which lacks detectable TRABs and would not explain the obstetrical history here.

